  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Pronouns (الضمائر)",
      "titleArabic": "الضمائر",
      "content": [
        "Arabic pronouns are divided into separate (munfaṣil) and attached (muttaṣil) forms. There are different sets for nominative (raf') and accusative/genitive (naṣb/jarr) cases."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Separate pronouns for raf': أَنَا, أَنْتَ, هُوَ, etc.",
        "Separate pronouns for naṣb: إِيَّاكَ, إِيَّاهُ, etc.",
        "Attached pronouns: ـهُ, ـكَ, ـي, etc.",
        "Use separate naṣb pronouns for emphasis or when unattached"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "إِيَّاكَ نَعْبُدُ", "english": "You alone we worship (emphasis)" },
        { "arabic": "رَأَيْتُهُ", "english": "I saw him (attached)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Conditional Sentences",
      "titleArabic": "الجملة الشرطية",
      "content": [
        "Conditional sentences consist of a condition (sharṭ) and response (jawāb). Different particles introduce different types of conditions."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "إِنْ: general/uncertain condition, causes jazm",
        "إِذَا: certain future condition",
        "لَوْ: unfulfilled past condition",
        "لَوْلَا: 'if not for' - counterfactual"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "إِنْ تَدْرُسْ تَنْجَحْ", "english": "If you study, you will succeed" },
        { "arabic": "لَوْ دَرَسَ لَنَجَحَ", "english": "If he had studied, he would have succeeded" }
      ]
    }
  ],
